# Label placement

Eunoia exposes two label-placement entry points: a **predicate**
(does my label fit?) and a **strategy-driven** placer (where should
my label go?). Both work in the same coordinate frame as the fitted
diagram and neither requires eunoia to know anything about your
fonts or text metrics — you measure, eunoia places.

## Mental model

Two functions, two return shapes:

| Entry point | Behaviour | Return |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `fit_labels_in_regions` (Rust) / `placeRegionLabelsForRegions` (npm) | Predicate: anchors the label at the region's pole of inaccessibility (POI) **only when** an axis-aligned `(w, h)` box fits inside the region polygon (with holes). | Map of regions where the label fits, omitting the rest. |
| `place_labels` (Rust) / `placeLabelsForRegions` (npm) | Strategy-driven: every requested region gets a position. Interior when the box fits; otherwise the chosen exterior policy decides. | Map of `LabelPlacement` per region, with a `kind` discriminator. |

Use the predicate when you want full control over what to do with
"doesn't fit" cases (smaller font, omit, exterior placement of your
own design). Use the strategy-driven placer when you want a sensible
default — it ships an exterior fallback with leader lines so you
never end up with a region that has nowhere to put its label.

`PlacementKind` carries which branch fired:

- `interior` — the box fits; anchor sits at the region's POI.
- `interiorOverflow` — reserved for the not-yet-implemented
  `loose` interior policy.
- `exteriorRaycast` — anchored outside the diagram bbox along the
  ray from the diagram centroid through the region's POI.
- `exteriorForceDirected` — initialised from the raycast position,
  then iteratively settled against label-vs-label collisions and
  foreign-region polygon repulsion.

For exterior kinds, `placement.tether` points back at the region's
POI so you can draw a leader line from the label to the region.

## Size measurement contract

**You measure, eunoia places.** Eunoia has no font or text metric
knowledge — it accepts label dimensions `(w, h)` in the same
coordinate units as the fitted shapes and tests whether an
axis-aligned rectangle of those dimensions inscribes inside the
region. How you measure is up to your renderer:

| Host | Typical measurement |
| --- | --- |
| SVG (DOM) | Render hidden `<text>` then `getBBox()`. |
| Canvas | `ctx.measureText(label)` (width) + font size (height). |
| R `grid` | `grid::convertWidth(grid::grobWidth(grob), "native")` and friends. |
| Python `matplotlib` | Renderer's `get_window_extent(...).transformed(ax.transData.inverted())`. |

Sizes are keyed by the **canonical combination string**:

- A single-set region is its set name: `"A"`.
- An intersection joins set names with `&` in canonical (sorted)
  order: `"A&B"`, `"A&B&C"`.
- The **complement region** (universe minus all sets, present when
  you fit with `complement: N`) keys as the empty string: `""`.

## Resize loop (size → place → measure)

Label sizes in user coordinates depend on the rendered canvas size
(font px / canvas-px ratio). For diagrams where labels land
exterior, the canvas extent in turn depends on label sizes —
labels stretch the bbox out. The fixed point typically converges in
one to three iterations.

### Native Rust — `place_labels_to_fixed_point`

```rust
use eunoia::plotting::{
    place_labels_to_fixed_point, ExteriorPolicy, InteriorPolicy,
    PlacementStrategy,
};

let placements = place_labels_to_fixed_point(
    &regions,
    container.as_ref(),
    initial_sizes,
    &PlacementStrategy::default(),
    |bbox| measure(bbox),       // your closure: bbox → sizes
    1e-3,                       // bbox tolerance (relative)
    8,                          // max iterations
)?;
```

### JavaScript / TypeScript

The npm wrapper doesn't ship a fixed-point helper because passing a
JS closure across the WASM boundary buys nothing — drive the loop in
JS:

```ts
import { placeLabelsForRegions, placementsBbox } from "@jolars/eunoia";

let sizes = measureLabels(initialBbox);
let placements = {};
for (let i = 0; i < 8; i++) {
  placements = placeLabelsForRegions({ regions, container, sizes });
  const bbox = placementsBbox({ placements, sizes });
  if (!bbox) break;
  const newSizes = measureLabels(bbox);
  if (closeEnough(sizes, newSizes)) break;
  sizes = newSizes;
}
```

### R / Python (sketch)

Same shape as the JS loop — host language drives `place →
placements_bbox → re-measure` until the canvas short side stops
moving.

```r
sizes <- measure_labels(initial_bbox)
for (i in 1:8) {
  placements <- place_region_labels(regions, container, sizes)
  bbox <- placements_bbox(placements, sizes)
  new_sizes <- measure_labels(bbox)
  if (close_enough(sizes, new_sizes)) break
  sizes <- new_sizes
}
```

## Strategy decision tree

The default strategy is `Strict` interior with `Raycast` exterior:

- **`Strict` interior** — anchor at POI only when the box fits;
  otherwise fall through to the exterior policy.
- **`Raycast` exterior** — deterministic ray from the diagram
  centroid through the region's POI; anchor lands outside the
  diagram bbox (or container, if you set one) padded by `margin`.
  Cheap, predictable, no surprises.
- **`ForceDirected` exterior** — warm-starts from the raycast
  positions, then iterates a soft spring (back to home) plus three
  repulsions: label-vs-label, label-vs-bbox containment along the
  raycast direction, and label-vs-foreign-region polygon repulsion.
  Default cap is 200 outer iterations.

Pick `Raycast` for typical n=2..3 diagrams or any case where labels
naturally spread around the perimeter. Reach for `ForceDirected`
when raycast labels visually overlap each other or land on top of
unrelated regions — for example, dense n=4 ellipse diagrams where
several intersection regions push their labels outward at similar
angles.

The two examples below are the same n=4 spec under each strategy.
Drag the page wider to see them side by side; the difference is
visible mostly when labels need exterior placement.

<DiagramExample
  sets={FOUR_SET_SPEC}
  shape="ellipse"
  strategy="raycast"
  caption="Strict + Raycast (default). Exterior labels follow the centroid→POI ray; collisions are resolved by a sweep that nudges along the perimeter."
/>

<DiagramExample
  sets={FOUR_SET_SPEC}
  shape="ellipse"
  strategy="forceDirected"
  caption="Strict + ForceDirected. Same warm-start positions, then iterated against label–label and label–region repulsion."
/>

Strategy knobs (defaults in parentheses):

- `margin` *(per-label proportional: `0.5 * max(w, h)`)* — padding
  between the diagram bbox / container and the label. The default
  scales with each label's own size, so a long string like
  `A&B&C&D` ends up further out than a short one. Override with a
  fixed value (e.g. `margin: 2`) when you want every exterior
  label flush to the diagram regardless of length.
- `iterations` *(200, ForceDirected only)* — outer iteration cap;
  inner label-vs-label sweep loops to disjointness so spring
  re-overlap doesn't leak into the converged result.
- `precision` *(0.01)* — polylabel-style search precision for the
  interior fit-check; smaller is more accurate, costlier.

## Rendering recipe

Pattern-match on `placement.kind`. Interior placements just need an
anchor; exterior placements also need a leader line back to
`placement.tether` (the region's POI):

```ts
for (const region of regions) {
  const p = placements[region.combination];
  if (!p) continue;
  if (p.kind === "exteriorRaycast" || p.kind === "exteriorForceDirected") {
    drawLine(p.tether!, p.anchor);   // leader line
  }
  drawLabel(p.anchor, region.combination);
}
```

The web app's [`DiagramSvg.svelte`](https://github.com/jolars/eunoia/blob/main/web/src/lib/components/DiagramSvg.svelte)
is the canonical SVG version — see the leader-line block around
line 575 and the `placementsBbox` canvas-extent block around line
100 for a complete reference renderer.

A few gotchas worth knowing:

- **Complement region key is the empty string.** When fitting with
  `complement: N`, the regions map includes a `combination === ""`
  entry whose pieces are the container minus the union of fitted
  shapes. Provide a size for `""` if you want to label it; omit it
  to leave the complement unlabelled.
- **Canvas extent depends on label sizes.** Use `placementsBbox`
  (or `placements_bbox` in Rust) to extend your viewBox / canvas to
  cover exterior labels — without it, exterior anchors land
  off-screen.
- **The placer separates labels to non-overlap, not to a visible
  gap.** If you want breathing room between adjacent labels (and
  you usually do), pad the sizes you pass in by your desired
  half-gap on every side, then render text at the original
  measured size. The two examples above use a 1-user-unit per-side
  pad for visible spacing.
- **Exterior anchors are placed relative to the diagram's
  axis-aligned bounding box**, not the union polygon of the fitted
  shapes. For circles and squares this is a tight proxy, but for
  ellipse arrangements it means a diagonal raycast can land in an
  AABB corner where no ellipse is anywhere near, with `margin`
  added past that. A tighter ray-vs-union-polygon implementation
  is on the roadmap; until then, override `margin` with a small
  fixed value if exterior labels look too far away on ellipse
  diagrams.
- **The interior fit-check uses a radial-conservative bound.** It
  never returns false positives (the inscribed rectangle is always
  strictly inside the region), but it can return false negatives
  for highly anisotropic regions. A tighter directional-clearance
  solver is on the roadmap; until then, prefer the strategy-driven
  placer over the predicate when you'd rather have *some* anchor
  than none.
